entrationary art—the need for an urgent and constant aesthetic resistance to the continuing effects of the concentrationary universe—proved to be a major influence for Hannah Arendt and other writers and theorists across a number of disciplines. Concentrationary Art presents the first translation into English of Jean Cayrol’s key essays on the subject, as well as the first book-length study of how we might situate and elaborate his concept of a Lazarean aesthetic in cultural theory, literature, cinema, music and contemporary art.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 04. Okt 2022) 0aArts, Frenchy20th century. 0aArts, Frenchy21st century. 0aConcentration camps in art. 0aConcentration camps in literature. 0aFrench literaturey20th centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aFrench literaturey21st centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aNazi concentration camps in art. 0aNazi concentration camps in literature. 0aRaising of Lazarus (Miracle) in art. 0aRaising of Lazarus (Miracle) in literature. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / European / French.2bisacsh  aJean Cayrol, Concentrationary, Post-war, Frankfurt School, Hannah Arendt.1 aCayrol, Jean, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCousen, Benjamin Hannavy, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFfrench, Patrick, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJohn, Matthew, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPollock, Griselda, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPollock, Griselda, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aSilverman, Max, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSilverman, Max, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertBerghah